#Text=The Pas
#Text=The Pas ( once Fort Paskoyac and still sometimes called Paskoyac ) is a small town in northern Manitoba .
#Text=The Pas is known as " Gateway to the North " .
#Text=It had about 5500 people in 2011 , a population roughly split between Aboriginals and non-Aboriginals .
#Text=Understand
#Text=It is approximately 630 km ( 390 mi ) northwest of the provincial capital , Winnipeg , and 40 km ( 25 mi ) from the border of Saskatchewan .
#Text=It is sometimes still called Paskoyac by locals after the first trading post , called Fort Paskoya and constructed during French colonial rule .
#Text=The Pasquia River begins in the Pasquia Hills in east central Saskatchewan .
#Text=The French in 1795 knew the river as Basquiau .
#Text=Known as " The Gateway to the North " , The Pas is a multi-industry northern Manitoba town serving the surrounding region .
#Text=The main components of the region 's economy are agriculture , forestry , commercial fishing , tourism , transportation , and services ( especially health and education ) .
#Text=The main employer is a paper and lumber mill operated by Canadian Kraft Papers .
#Text=The Pas contains one of the two main campuses of the University College of the North .
#Text=The Pas is bordered by part of the Opaskwayak Cree Nation .
#Text=The Pas experiences a humid continental climate with long cold winters and short warm summers .
#Text=By car
#Text=The Pas is 626 km ( about 6½-9 hours ) north of Winnipeg on Highways 6 and 60 .
#Text=By train
#Text=Via Rail goes once a day , leaving at 12:05PM and arriving 13 hr 40 min later at 1:45AM ( $ 85 - 290 ) .
#Text=By bus
#Text=Maple Bus Lines Service to Winnipeg and Thompson .
#Text=By plane
#Text=The Pas Airport ( YQD ) .
#Text=There is one direct flight a day from Winnipeg ( YWG ) to The Pas on Calm Air ( 1 hr 40 min , $ 440 ) , and one flight that stops at Flin Flon ( YFO ) .
#Text=Get around
#Text=Cal 's Can , ☏ +1 204-623-3333 . 24 hours .
#Text=See
#Text=Northern Manitoba Trappers ' Festival , ☏ +1 204-623-2912 .
#Text=Manitoba 's oldest festival and one of Canada ’s oldest winter festival .

#Text=It has been held every year continuously since 1948 and features a wide variety of winter activities including ice fishing , muskrat skinning , and an annual sled dog race , which is part of the International Federation of Sleddog Sports .
#Text=Do
#Text=Clearwater Lake Provincial Park , ☏ +1204 627-8287 .
#Text=This park has an area of 593 km ² .
#Text=Clearwater Lake comprises almost half of the park .
#Text=Large areas of boreal forest including spruce bog cover the land areas .
#Text=Clearwater Lake , a deep , clear , cold lake , is renowned for its excellent water quality and large lake trout .
#Text=The nearly circular lake , 16 km ( 10 mi ) in diameter , has an average depth of 13.1 m ( 43 ft ) and a maximum depth of 39 m ( 127 ft ) .
#Text=It is spring-fed and lacks major inflowing streams which may carry silt , although there are several small inflowing streams on its south and west shores .
#Text=Campgrounds are on the south shore .
#Text=Vehicle permit : $5/day , $12/3 days .
